<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="32" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,334,670]" pageId="9" pageNumber="32">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,328,488,514]" pageId="9" pageNumber="32">Diagnosis:</emphasis>
This species is recognized by the presence of cone-shaped tubercles on posterior corners of carapace dorsal surface (
<figureCitation box="[439,569,528,554]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 A – U" captionStartId="3.[151,270,1873,1897]" captionTargetBox="[191,1396,167,1847]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[191,1397,167,1849]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1 A – U. Opopaea cornuta Yin &amp; Wang, 1984 (B, K); Opopaea deserticola Simon, 1891 (Q, S, T); Opopaea diaoluoshan sp. nov. (C, H, I); Opopaea furcula sp. nov. (E, O); Opopaea gibbifera Tong &amp; Li, 2008 (D, L); Opopaea sanya sp. nov. (F, M); Opopaea sauteri Brignoli, 1974 (G, N, P, R, U) and Opopaea vitrispina sp. nov. (A, J). A – G. Male habitus, dorsal view; H. Male abdomen, ventral view; I – O. Male habitus, lateral view; P, Q. Male left palp, prolateral view; R, S. Female genitalia, ventral view; T, U. Female carapace, dorsal view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/205794/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="32">
Figs 
<number box="[498,509,528,554]" pageId="9" pageNumber="32" value="1.0">1</number>
D, L
</figureCitation>
), the large palpal depression and long outgrowths on male palpal embolus (
<figureCitation box="[159,346,566,592]" captionStart="FIGURES 11 A – H" captionStartId="17.[151,269,1936,1960]" captionTargetBox="[206,1381,155,1918]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[206,1393,152,1918]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURES 11 A – H. Opopaea gibbifera Tong &amp; Li, 2008, left male palp, SEM. A. Prolateral view; B. Retrolateral view; C. Bulb, prolateral view; D. Bulb, retrolateral view; E. Palpal depression, prolateral view; F. Ditto, retrolateral view; G. Tip of embolus, prolateral view; H. Tip of embolus, retrolateral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/205805/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="32">
Figs 
<number box="[222,250,566,592]" pageId="9" pageNumber="32" value="11.0">11</number>
A, C, E
</figureCitation>
, see 
<bibRefCitation author="Tong" box="[407,617,566,592]" pageId="9" pageNumber="43" refString="Tong, Y. F. &amp; Li, S. Q. (2008) The oonopid spiders (Araneae: Oonopidae) from Hainan Island, China. Raffles Bulletin of Zoology, 56, 55 - 66." type="journal article" year="2008">
Tong &amp; Li, 
<number box="[552,617,566,592]" pageId="9" pageNumber="32" value="2008.0">2008</number>
</bibRefCitation>
: figs 
<number box="[684,699,566,592]" pageId="9" pageNumber="32" value="7.0">7</number>
F, G) and small triangular shaped anterior edge of postgynal depression of female (
<figureCitation box="[411,505,605,631]" captionStart="FIGURES 2 A – G" captionStartId="4.[151,269,1942,1966]" captionTargetBox="[235,1372,155,1941]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[228,1379,149,1941]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 2 A – G. Opopaea cornuta Yin &amp; Wang, 1984 (A – E) and Opopaea gibbifera Tong &amp; Li, 2008 (F – G). A. Male left palp, prolateral view; B. Male left palp, retrolateral view; C. Female scutopetiolar apparatus, anteroventral view; D, G. Female postgynum, ventral view; E, F. Vulva, dorsal view. Scale lines = 0.1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/205795/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="32">
